<!-- ABSTRACT -->
<section id="abstract">
  <div class="abstract-wrap">
    <div class="section-eyebrow" style="text-align:center">Project Abstract</div>
    <h2 class="section-title" style="text-align:center;max-width:none">The Scope of EruvGuard</h2>
    <div class="blue-bar" style="margin:10px auto 28px"></div>
    <div class="abstract-card">
      <p>
        EruvGuard is a student-developed engineering project designed to address a critical and underserved need within Modern Orthodox Jewish communities: the reliable, real-time monitoring of an eruv. An eruv is a symbolic boundary — typically a continuous wire or string — that permits certain activities on Shabbat and Jewish holidays. Because even a single break in this boundary renders the entire eruv invalid, maintaining its integrity is an ongoing religious and logistical responsibility. Traditional inspection methods require dedicated volunteers to physically walk or drive the eruv perimeter each week, an effort that consumes significant time and is prone to human error.
        <br><br>
        EruvGuard addresses this challenge through an integrated hardware-software system that uses an accelerometer to detect positional changes in the eruv line, a solar-powered ESP32 microcontroller to process and transmit data, and a web-based alert interface to instantly notify community leaders when a disruption is detected. The system stores excess solar energy in rechargeable lithium batteries, ensuring continuous operation regardless of weather conditions.
        <br><br>
        Existing automated eruv systems — such as those deployed in Manhattan — can cost upwards of $200,000 annually and are custom-built for specific eruvin, making them inaccessible to the vast majority of communities. EruvGuard's goal is to deliver a low-cost, universally adaptable, and low-maintenance alternative that makes automated eruv supervision achievable for communities of any size, anywhere.
      </p>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>

<!-- PROBLEM -->
<section id="problem">
  <div class="section-eyebrow">The Problem</div>
  <h2 class="section-title">Why the Eruv Needs a Guardian</h2>
  <div class="blue-bar"></div>
  <p class="section-subtitle">The eruv is essential to Modern Orthodox Jewish life — but its physical nature makes it uniquely vulnerable. Communities deserve a better solution.</p>
  <div class="problem-grid">
    <div class="problem-card">
      <div class="p-icon">🕍</div>
      <h4>Sacred &amp; Essential</h4>
      <p>The eruv is foundational to Modern Orthodox life, permitting carrying on Shabbat and Yom Tov. Its validity directly affects every member of the community and their religious observance each week.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="problem-card">
      <div class="p-icon">⚠️</div>
      <h4>Fragile by Nature</h4>
      <p>The eruv depends on an unbroken, continuous physical boundary. Even a single small break — caused by weather, fallen branches, or loose attachments — invalidates the entire structure immediately.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="problem-card">
      <div class="p-icon">🔍</div>
      <h4>Invisible Failures</h4>
      <p>Breaks can occur without anyone noticing. A community may unknowingly carry on Shabbat, creating serious halachic concerns that could have been avoided with timely automated detection.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="problem-card">
      <div class="p-icon">⏱️</div>
      <h4>Time-Consuming Maintenance</h4>
      <p>Weekly inspections of large eruvin demand hours of volunteer time — a burden that falls on a small, dedicated group week after week, with no backup if someone is unavailable.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- SOLUTION -->
<section id="solution">
  <div class="section-eyebrow">Our Solution</div>
  <h2 class="section-title">Introducing EruvGuard</h2>
  <div class="blue-bar"></div>
  <p class="section-subtitle">A smart, scalable monitoring system that keeps watch 24/7 — so community leaders can focus on what matters most.</p>
  <div class="features-grid">
    <div class="feature-card">
      <div class="f-icon">⚡</div>
      <h4>Real-Time Alerts</h4>
      <p>The moment a break is detected, responsible parties receive an immediate notification with the approximate location — no waiting until the next scheduled inspection.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature-card">
      <div class="f-icon">🔧</div>
      <h4>Faster Repairs</h4>
      <p>Instant alerts enable same-day response, ensuring the eruv is valid before Shabbat rather than after a problem is discovered too late to fix.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature-card">
      <div class="f-icon">🚶</div>
      <h4>Less Manual Work</h4>
      <p>Eliminates exhaustive weekly perimeter walks. Inspectors spend their time on targeted repairs — not covering ground that's already being monitored automatically.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature-card">
      <div class="f-icon">✅</div>
      <h4>Improved Reliability</h4>
      <p>Continuous automated monitoring means unnoticed breaks become a thing of the past — delivering greater halachic confidence and peace of mind for the entire community.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature-card">
      <div class="f-icon">📡</div>
      <h4>Scalable for Any Eruv</h4>
      <p>Whether your eruv spans a single block or an entire town, EruvGuard adapts to any scale — a universally adaptable solution, not a custom, one-community system.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature-card">
      <div class="f-icon">☮️</div>
      <h4>Reduced Community Stress</h4>
      <p>Eliminates weekly anxiety about eruv status. Community members enter Shabbat with confidence, knowing the eruv is actively watched around the clock.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- HOW IT WORKS -->
<section id="how-it-works">
  <div class="section-eyebrow">Technology</div>
  <h2 class="section-title">How EruvGuard Works</h2>
  <div class="blue-bar"></div>
  <p class="section-subtitle">Four integrated components form a self-sustaining, always-on monitoring system that attaches directly to an existing eruv line.</p>
  <div class="steps-grid">
    <div class="step-card">
      <div class="step-num">01</div>
      <div>
        <div class="step-tag">Fall Detection</div>
        <h4>Accelerometer Monitoring</h4>
        <p>An accelerometer continuously tracks the position of the eruv line. When a break occurs, the device registers a significant positional change and immediately triggers an alert — distinguishing real breaks from normal environmental movement.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-card">
      <div class="step-num">02</div>
      <div>
        <div class="step-tag">Alert System</div>
        <h4>ESP32 Web Interface</h4>
        <p>An ESP32 microcontroller processes signals from the accelerometer and transmits real-time alerts to an HTML-based web dashboard. The eruv manager receives an immediate, location-specific notification the moment a disruption is detected.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-card">
      <div class="step-num">03</div>
      <div>
        <div class="step-tag">Renewable Energy</div>
        <h4>Solar Panel Power</h4>
        <p>A compact solar panel provides continuous, renewable power to the ESP32 and all connected components during daylight hours — eliminating manual battery replacements and keeping the system fully self-sufficient in the field.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-card">
      <div class="step-num">04</div>
      <div>
        <div class="step-tag">Reserve Power</div>
        <h4>Lithium Battery Backup</h4>
        <p>Rechargeable lithium batteries store excess solar energy to ensure EruvGuard operates continuously through the night and on overcast days — so no break goes undetected regardless of conditions.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

